ms]]\n[[Category:FIFA (video game series) teams]]\n[[Category:Hearthstone teams]]\n[[Category:Heroes of the Storm teams]]\n[[Category:League of Legends European Championship teams]]\n[[Category:Super Smash Bros. player sponsors]]\n[[Category:Rocket League teams]]\n[[Category:Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six Siege teams]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox sports team\n| name = G2 Esports\n| short_name = G2\n| logo = G2 Esports logo.png\n| logo_size =\n| alt =\n| caption =\n| sport_label = Divisions\n| sport = {{nowrap|''[[League of Legends]]''<br />''[[Counter-Strike: Global Offensive]]''<br />''[[Rainbow Six Siege]]''<br />''[[Fortnite]]''<br />'' [[Hearthstone]]''<br />''[[PLAYERUNKNOWN'S BATTLEGROUNDS]]''<br />''[[Rocket League]]''<br />''[[iRacing]]''}}\n| founded = {{start date|2014|02|24|df=yes}} (as Gamers2)<br />15 October 2015 (as G2 Esports)\n| location = [[Berlin]], [[Germany]]\n| owner = Carlos \"ocelote\" Rodr\u00edguez Santiago<br />[[Jens Hilgers]]\n| manager = Roberto \"Goro\" Irusta ([[Chief gaming officer|CGO]])\n| fanclub =\n| parent_group =\n| folded =\n| website = {{URL|www.g2esports.com/}}\n| footnotes =\n| partners = [[AOC International|AOC]], [[AORUS]], Hdac Technology AG, [[Logitech]], [[Mastercard]], nicecactus, [[paysafecard]], [[Twitch (service)|Twitch]]\n| blank_data = [[United States dollar|US$]]6.83 million<ref>{{cite web |title=Highest Overall Team Earnings |url=https://www.esportsearnings.com/teams |publisher=Esports Earnings |accessdate=December 23, 2019}}</ref>\n| blank_label = Earnings\n}}\n\n'''G2 Esports''', formerly known as '''Gamers2''', is a [[Spain|Spanish]] [[esports]] organisation based in [[Berlin]], [[Germany]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=535269394 |title=G Esports Holding GmbH: Private Company Information |publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]] |access-date=19 March 2018}}</ref> with players competing in ''[[League of Legends]]'', ''[[Counter-Strike: Global Offensive]]'', ''[[PLAYERUNKNOWN'S BATTLEGROUNDS]]'', ''[[Hearthstone (video game)|Hearthstone]]'', ''[[Rocket League]]'', ''[[Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six Siege|Rainbow Six Siege]]'', and ''[[iRacing]]''. The organization was founded on 24 February 2014 by former ''League of Legends'' pro Carlos \"ocelote\" Rodr\u00edguez Santiago and investor [[Jens Hilgers]].\n\nG2's ''League of Legends'' team competes in the [[League of Legends European Championship|''League of Legends'' European Championship]] (LEC), the highest level of competitive ''League of Legends'' in Europe. The team won the [[2016 Spring EU LCS|2016 Spring]], [[2016 Summer European League of Legends Championship Series|2016 Summer]], 2017 Spring, and 2017 Summer EU LCS, the 2019 Spring LEC, the [[2019 Mid-Season Invitational]] and the 2019 Summer LEC.\n\n== ''League of Legends'' ==\n{{Infobox sports team\n| name = G2 Esports\n| game = ''[[League of Legends]]''\n| founded =\n| folded =\n| current =\n| league = [[League of Legends European Championship|LEC]]\n| conference =\n| division =\n| colors =\n| coach = Fabian \"GrabbZ\" Lohmann\n| gm =\n| championships = 1\u00d7 [[Mid-Season Invitational|MSI]] ([[2019 Mid-Season Invitational|2019]])\n{{Collapsible list\n| title = {{nobold|6\u00d7 [[League of Legends European Championship|LEC]]}}\n| [[2016 Spring European League of Legends Championship Series|2016 Spring]]\n| [[2016 Summer European League of Legends Championship Series|2016 Summer]]\n| 2017 Spring\n| 2017 Summer\n| 2019 Spring\n| 2019 Summer\n}}\n}}\n\n=== History ===\nGamers2 had made a start for ''League of Legends'' in 2014 with an initial roster of Top laner Jesper \"Jwaow\" Strandgren, jungler Sebasti\u00e1n \"Morden\" Esteban Fern\u00e1ndez, AD carry Soler \"Yuuki60\" Florent, and support Hugo \"Dioud\" Padioleau.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gfinity.net/news/details/league-of-legends-pro-ocelote-retires|title=League of Legends Pro \"ocelote\" Retires|author=KRAZYSLAYER187|website=Gfininty|date=18 February 2015|accessdate=3 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://2015.na.lolesports.com/articles/how-ocelote-built-gamers-2-ground|title=HOW OCELOTE BUILT GAMERS 2 FROM THE GROUND UP|first=Taylor ''Riot RoboTayCo''|last=Cocke|website=LoL Esports|publisher=[[Riot Games]]|date=3 December 2015|accessdate=3 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304104618/http://2015.na.lolesports.com/articles/how-ocelote-built-gamers-2-ground|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe team participated in the Spring Expansion Tournament, beating Reason Gaming in the seeding game and Team Strix in Round 1. Gamers2 were knocked out of the tournament in Round 2 after being beaten by n!faculty.\n\nG2 Esports was renamed from Gamers2 after qualifying for the 2016 EU LCS Spring Season.<ref name=\"dd ocelot\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailydot.com/esports/ocelote-gamers2-lcs-csgo/|title=Ocelote on Gamers2 rebranding plans and how he's building 'a world class esports club'|first=Josh|last=Raven|website=[[The Daily Dot]]|date=29 September 2015|accessdate=3 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305014522/http://www.dailydot.com/esports/ocelote-gamers2-lcs-csgo/|archive-date=5 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nG2 Esports has also a sister team in Spain competing in the EU Challenger Series, called G2 Vodafone, in representation of their sponsor Vodafone. They qualified for the 2016 EU Challenger Series Summer Split Qualifiers, but failed to qualify for the EU CS. They also won the Spanish 2016 FinalCup Spring Split.\n\nThe team failed to qualify for the LCS three splits in a row.<ref name=\"dd ocelot\"/>\n\nThe team finished 1st in the Challenger Series season. They then took 2nd in the playoffs, thereby qualifying for the 2016 Spring LCS. Gamers2 qualified for the LCS by defeating [[SK Gaming]] 3\u20132.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailydot.com/esports/gamers2-gambit-lcs/|title=Gamers2 and Gambit qualify for the LCS|first=Josh|last=Raven|website=[[The Daily Dot]]|date=5 September 2015|accessdate=1 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150926140928/http://www.dailydot.com/esports/gamers2-gambit-lcs/|archive-date=26 September 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nG2 finished the [[2016 Spring European League of Legends Championship Series|2016 EU LCS Spring Split]] regular season in 1st place. In the playoffs, they defeated [[Fnatic]] before winning the 2016 EU LCS in Rotterdam after beating [[Origen (esports)|Origen]]. This also meant that they had qualified for the [[2016 Mid-Season Invitational]] tournament in Shanghai. G2 would represent Europe at the competition against 5 other teams. However, in the weeks before the tournament, the team took an infamous vacation and came to the tournament unprepared. Because of this, they lost 8 of their 10 games, their only two wins against the lowest ranked seed there. This also cost the EU LCS league its 1st seed for the [[2016 League of Legends World Championship|2016 World Championship]] later that year. This meant that the 1st seed for Europe of the [[2016 Summer League of Legends Championship Series|2016 Summer EU LCS]] would be put in Pot B for the group draw instead of Pot A.\n\nG2 became the first team to be crowned LEC champions after they won its inaugural split on 14 April 2019, in a 3\u20130 sweep against Origen.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Esguerra |first1=Tyler |title=G2 Esports destroy Origen to win 2019 LEC Spring Split finals |url=https://dotesports.com/league-of-legends/news/g2-destroy-origen-win-2019-lec-spring-finals |accessdate=18 April 2019 |work=Dot Esports |date=14 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter sweeping [[Team Liquid]] from North America 3\u20130 in the grand final of the [[2019 Mid-Season Invitational]], G2 became the first European team to win a Riot-sponsored international tournament since Fnatic won the Season 1 World Championship.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Amos |first1=Andrew |title=G2 smash Team Liquid to become the MSI 2019 champions |url=https://dotesports.com/league-of-legends/news/g2-are-the-msi-2019-champions-smashing-team-liquid |accessdate=15 June 2019 |work=Dot Esports |date=19 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Stubbs |first1=Mike |title=G2 Esports Win 'League of Legends' MSI 2019 Tournament |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/mikestubbs/2019/05/19/g2-esports-win-league-of-legends-msi-2019-tournament/#10844d0a3f80 |accessdate=15 June 2019 |work=Forbes |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThey finished first in the 2019 LEC Summer Split regular season and later defeated Fnatic 3\u20132 in the finals to secure their sixth domestic title.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Samples |first1=Rachel |title=G2 Esports crowned LEC Summer Split champions after taking down Fnatic |url=https://dotesports.com/league-of-legends/news/g2-esports-crowned-lec-summer-split-champions-after-taking-down-fnatic |accessdate=9 September 2019 |work=Dot Esports |date=8 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Kolev |first1=Radoslav |title=G2 Esports beat Fnatic, crowned 2019 LEC Summer champions |url=https://www.vpesports.com/leagueoflegends/news/g2-esports-beat-fnatic-crowned-2019-lec-summer-champions |accessdate=9 September 2019 |work=VPEsports |date=8 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2019 League of Legends World Championship|2019 ''League of Legends'' World Championship]], G2 finished runner-up, losing to Chinese team [[FunPlus Phoenix]] in the grand finals.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://win.gg/news/2934/funplus-phoenix-trounce-g2-esports-win-lol-worlds-2019-finals |title=FunPlus Phoenix trounce G2 Esports, win LoL Worlds 2019 finals |website=win.gg |accessdate=10 November 2019 |date=10 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n== ''Counter-Strike: Global Offensive'' ==\n\n=== History ===\nG2 Esports acquired the roster of Team Kinguin on 11 September 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://1337mag.com/7675-gamers2-signs-on-the-team-kinguin-csgo-squad|title=Gamers2 Signs on the Team Kinguin CS:GO Squad|first=Rasmus|last=Lund-Hansen|website=[[1337 Magazine]]|date=11 September 2015|accessdate=1 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150915014504/http://1337mag.com/7675-gamers2-signs-on-the-team-kinguin-csgo-squad|archive-date=15 September 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> G2 finished 3rd\u20134th at [[DreamHack]] Open: [[Cluj-Napoca]] 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailydot.com/esports/counter-strike-envy-navi-dreamhack/|title=EnvyUs deny Na`Vi's breakthrough win|first=Jared|last=Wynne|website=[[The Daily Dot]]|date=2 November 2015|accessdate=3 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161110200544/http://www.dailydot.com/esports/counter-strike-envy-navi-dreamhack/|archive-date=10 November 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> On 20 January 2016 G2 Esports announced that [[FaZe Clan]] had acquired their international Counter-Strike roster.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.g2esports.com/g2-csgo-team-acquired-by-faze/|title=G2's Counter-Strike team acquired by FaZe Clan|website=G2 Esports|date=20 January 2016|accessdate=20 January 2016}}</ref> G2 announced a new French-speaking roster on 1 February 2016<ref>{{cite web|title=G2.Kinguin presents new CS:GO team|url=http://www.g2esports.com/g2kinguin-presents-new-csgo-team|website=g2esports.com|accessdate=1 February 2016}}</ref> which consisted of [[Titan (esports)|Titan]]'s former roster. On 9 April, shortly after placing 9\u201312th at the [[MLG Major Championship: Columbus]], G2 announced Alexandre \"bodyy\" Pianaro would be replacing K\u00e9vin \"Ex6TenZ\" Droolans.<ref>{{cite web|title=G2 welcomes bodyy to CS:GO team|url=http://www.g2esports.com/g2-welcomes-bodyy-to-csgo-team/|website=G2 Esports|accessdate=9 April 2016}}</ref> G2 placed 2nd at the ESL Pro League Season 3 Finals on 16 May 2016 after losing 2\u20133 to [[Luminosity Gaming]] in the grand finals.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Guevarra|first1=Earl|title=Luminosity Gaming Wins ESL CS:GO Pro League Season 3 in Nailbiter Series|url=http://esports.inquirer.net/15161/luminosity-gaming|website=Inquirer.net|accessdate=18 May 2016}}</ref> G2 Esports won the [[Faceit|Esports Championship Series]] Season 1 after beating Luminosity in the finals on 26 June 2016.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mira|first1=Luis|title=G2 beat Luminosity to win ECS S1|url=http://www.hltv.org/news/18148-g2-beat-luminosity-to-win-ecs-s1|website=HLTV.org|accessdate=28 June 2016}}</ref> With effect from 3 February 2017, 3 players from Team EnVyUs have joined G2 Esports. Kenny \"kennyS\" Schrub, Dan \"apEX\" Madesclaire and Nathan \"NBK\" Schmitt thus forming the now called \"French Super Team\". The players they replaced were Adil \"ScreaM\" Benrlitom, who joined Team EnVyUs, C\u00e9dric \"RpK\" Guipouy, who also joined Team EnVyUs and Edouard \"SmithZz\" Dubourdeaux who is now the head coach of G2 Esports.\nOn June 4, 2018, SmithZz and Ex6TenZ replace apEX and NBK- in the lineup.<ref>https://www.hltv.org/news/23845/shox-returns-to-g2-ahead-of-ecs-finals-nbk-apex-benched</ref>\nOn October 8, 2018, apEX and NBK- left G2 after being acquired by Team Vitality.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.talkesport.com/news/g2-announce-departures-of-apex-and-nbk-following-their-transfer-to-vitality/|title=G2 announce departures of Apex and NBK following their transfer to Vitality \u00bb TalkEsport|last=Gada|first=Parth|date=2018-10-08|website=TalkEsport|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\nIn November 2018, Jackz and Lucky joined G2 while SmithZz and Ex6TenZ move to the bench.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hltv.org/news/25470/jackz-and-lucky-join-g2-smithzz-and-ex6tenz-benched|title=JaCkz and Lucky join G2; SmithZz and Ex6TenZ benched|website=HLTV.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\nOn March 8, 2019, AmaNEk joined G2 replacing bodyy in the active lineup.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.talkesport.com/news/g2-signs-amannek-bodyy-benched/|title=G2 signs AmanNEk; Bodyy benched \u00bb TalkEsport|last=Popat|first=Malav|date=2019-03-08|website=TalkEsport|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://g2esports.com/2019/03/07/welcome-amanek-csgo-roster-update/|title=Welcome AMANEK - CS:GO Roster Update|date=2019-03-06|website=G2 Esports|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\nOn 30 September 2019, G2 acquired Nexa and Hunter from CR4ZY replacing Lucky and Shox in the lineup.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.g2esports.com/g2-csgo-goes-global/|title=G2 CS:GO Goes Global|date=30 September 2019|website=G2 Esports|language=en-US|access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Achievements ===\n* 1st \u2013 [[DreamHack]] Open Tours 2017<ref name=\"G2 CS:GO win Dreamhack Tours\">{{cite web|title=G2 beat HR to win DreamHack Tours|url=https://www.hltv.org/news/20426/g2-beat-hr-to-win-dreamhack-tours|website=hltv.org|accessdate=8 May 2017}}</ref>\n* 1st \u2013 [[ESL Pro League Season 5]]<ref name=\"G2 CS:GO win EPL S5\">{{cite web|title=G2 Esports win ESL Pro League Season 5|url=http://fragbite.com/cs/news/40846/g2-esports-win-esl-pro-league-season-5|website=fragbite.com|accessdate=5 June 2017}}</ref>\n* 1st \u2013 [[DreamHack]] Masters Malm\u00f6 2017<ref name=\"G2 CS:GO win Dreamhack Masters Malmo\">{{cite web|title=G2 win DH Masters Malm\u00f6 over North|url=http://fragbite.com/cs/news/41309/g2-win-dh-masters-malmo-over-north|website=fragbite.com|accessdate=3 September 2017}}</ref>\n* 3rd \u2013 EPICENTER 2017<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fragbite.com/cs/news/41633/epicenter-2017-sk-gaming-overcome-virtuspro |title=Epicenter 2017 \u2013 SK Gaming overcome Virtus.pro |publisher=Fragbite.com |accessdate=4 May 2018}}</ref>\n* 5th \u2013 BLAST Pro Series Copenhagen 2017\n* 7th \u2013 [[ESL Pro League Season 6]] Europe\n* 9th\u201310th [[Intel Extreme Masters Season 12 \u2013 Oakland]]\n\n== ''Super Smash Bros. Melee'' ==\nG2 Esports signed [[Weston \"Westballz\" Dennis]] on 11 July 2016 but Dennis and G2 parted ways on 31 March 2019 .<ref>{{cite web|title=G2 expands into Super Smash Bros Melee|url=http://www.g2esports.com/g2-expands-super-smash-bros/|website=G2 Esports|accessdate=11 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n== ''Rocket League'' ==\n\n=== History ===\nG2 Esports signed the RLCS Season One World Champions, former iBUYPOWER Cosmic on 7 September 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=G2 Esports sign Rocket League World Champions.|url=http://www.g2esports.com/g2-esports-sign-rocket-league-world-champions/|website=G2 Esports|accessdate=3 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nLachinio and 0verZer0 left the team, and Rizzo and Jknaps were picked up on 22 February 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.g2esports.com/jknaps-rizzo-join-rocket-league-team/ |title=G2 Esports {{!}} JKnaps & Rizzo join Rocket League team |publisher=G2 Esports |date=22 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe team won the ELEAGUE Cup 2017 tournament after missing RLCS season 3,<ref>G2 esports win Eleague Cup https://liquipedia.net/rocketleague/ELEAGUE/Cup</ref> and placed 2nd at Dreamhack Leipzig 2018.<ref>G2 esports takes second at Dreamhack https://liquipedia.net/rocketleague/DreamHack/2018/Leipzig</ref>\n\nThe team finished 7th\u20138th at the RLCS World Championship Season 5, despite being the No. 1 seed from North America.<ref>Rocket League Championship Series Season 5 \u2013 Finals https://liquipedia.net/rocketleague/Rocket_League_Championship_Series/Season_5</ref>\n\nThe team finished 9th\u201310th at the RLCS World Championship Season 6, despite being the No. 2 seed from North America.<ref>Rocket League Championship Series Season 6 \u2013 Finals https://liquipedia.net/rocketleague/Rocket_League_Championship_Series/Season_6</ref>\n\nOn 7 January 2019, the team dropped former captain Kronovi, and picked up Chicago from [[Evil Geniuses]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.g2esports.com/g2-rocket-league-chicago/ |title=G2 Esports {{!}} G2 Rocket League Update: Welcome, Chicago! |publisher=G2 Esports |date=7 January 2019}}</ref> Kronovi went on to join [[Rogue (esports)|Rogue]].<ref>{{cite tweet |user=GoingRogueGG |number=1082368713481957377 |date= 7 January 2019 |title=We at Rogue are extremely excited to welcome our Rocket League lineup for 2019! Let us know what you think! }}</ref> G2 then finished 2nd at the RLCS World Championship Season 7 with Chicago.<ref>Rocket League Championship Series Season 7 \u2013 Finals\nhttps://liquipedia.net/rocketleague/Rocket_League_Championship_Series/Season_7|</ref>\n\nAfter finishing second in League Play, G2 faced NRG in the semifinals of the RLCS Season 9 NA Regional Championship, winning 4-3 in a close Game 7 to put them through to the grand finals to face Spacestation Gaming. They would go on to sweep Spacestation, crowning them the RLCS Season 9 North American Champions.<ref>Rocket League Championship Series Season 9 \u2013 North America https://liquipedia.net/rocketleague/Rocket_League_Championship_Series/Season_9/North_America</ref>\n\n== ''Clash Royale'' ==\nG2 Esports signed with Supercell to join in Clash Royale League (CRL) on 3 April 2018.\n\n== ''Rainbow Six Siege'' ==\n\n=== History ===\nThe announcement that G2 Esports acquired the full roster of PENTA Sports, all five players and two coaches came a few days before the kick-off of the Six Major Paris group stage. These players, winners of the Six Invitational 2018 and multiple Pro League champions, have represented the colors of G2 from 10 August 2018 onward.  The team quickly proved to be a beneficial pick-up by G2, winning the Six Major Paris and its $350,000 prize pool immediately following the purchase by defeating their rivals [[Evil Geniuses]] 3\u20130.<ref>{{cite news |title=G2 Esports Win $350,000 Rainbow Six Major Paris 2018 \u2013 Final Placements |url=https://www.dexerto.com/rainbow-six/g2-esports-win-rainbow-six-major-paris---final-placements-143259 |accessdate=28 March 2019 |work=Dexerto.com}}</ref>\n\nThe team won the Six Invitational 2019 (world championship) on 17 February 2019 by defeating Team Empire 3\u20130.<ref>{{cite news |title=G2 Esports cement Rainbow Six dynasty at Six Invitational |url=http://www.espn.com/esports/story/_/id/26021321/g2-esports-cement-rainbow-six-dynasty-six-invitational |accessdate=27 March 2019 |work=ESPN.com |date=18 February 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nAfter signing UUNO and dropping JNSzki, G2 lost the Six Major Raleigh on 18 August 2019 after losing 3\u20131 to Russian rivals, Team Empire.\n\n=== Players and coaches ===\nPengu is the most experienced player in both the team and the Rainbow Six Siege pro league, having been in the Year 1 Season 1 'PENTA' roster which would eventually transform into G2 Esports. Fabian is the IGL (In Game Leader) of the team to whom the strategic success and flexibility of the team is often pointed towards, as one of the best IGLs in the European pro league and the pro league in general. Goga is the only non-Nordic player on the team, and the only Spanish player in the whole of pro league. He is often praised for his ability on the games hard breachers, particularly Thermite, and who's support based playstyle has led to him having the highest amount of plants of a player in the European pro league season. JNSzki was one of the 2 Finnish players on the team, being acquired from PENTA's Year 1 rival of GiFu, he has been reputed throughout the pro league's history as one of the best aimers and Bandit players in all of Siege. JNSzki was released by G2 ESports on 27 May 2019, replaced by Finnish player UUNO of LeStream (Now [[Rogue (esports)|Rogue]]). Kantoraketti, originally being a loan to PENTA (Now G2) from ENCE for the LAN finals of season 7 Pro League. Following the departure of prior teammate SHA77E from PENTA, Kantoraketti officially became the 5th member of PENTA. UUNO, the newest addition to the roster was acquired by G2 Esports on 27 May 2019 replacing JNSzki who returned to his former squad of [[Mousesports]] which both players were once apart of. UUNO had played for the PENTA Academy being coached by G2's own coach, Shas[O]Uas (Shas). Shas is one of the longest working coaches in siege, originally coaching for Team Fenix, a team which had also featured Fabian and previous roster teammate of KS, and is the head coach for the team. Sua is the secondary coach and analyst of the roster, brought in to replace Ferral, G2's original analyst and a current player for [[Team Secret]]. Sua was previously the head coach of [[ENCE Esports]], the previous team of jNSzki, SHA77E, and Kantoraketti (Now GiFu Esports). On 22 November 2019, Goga was replaced by the German player of Pascal \"Cry1NNN\" Alouane.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://dotesports.com/rainbow-6/news/cryn-joins-g2-esports-goga-departs-r6-roster|title=Cryn joins G2 Esports, Goga departs R6 roster|date=2019-11-22|website=Dot Esports|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref>\n\n==== Former Players ====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!{{abbr|Nat.|Nationality}}\n!Name\n!ID\n!Role\n!Join Date\n!Leave Date\n!Next Team\n!Current Team\n|-\n|{{flagicon|UK}}\n|Daniel Rotherham\n|Ferral\n|Analyst\n|2018-08-10<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.g2esports.com/g2-rainbow-six-siege/|title=The world\u2019s best Rainbow Six Siege Team joins G2 Esports!|date=2018-08-10|website=G2 Esports|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref>\n|2019-02-06<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/G2esports/status/1093186370053517312|title=We also bid a farewell to @G2Ferral! Thank You for all the hard work over the best few months!  Best of luck, Ferral!|last=Esports|first=G2|date=2019-02-06|website=@G2esports|language=en|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref>\n|[[Vexed Gaming]]\n|[[Team Secret]]\n|-\n|{{flagicon|FIN}}\n|Joonas Savolainen\n|jNSzki\n|Flex\n|2018-08-10<ref name=\":1\" />\n|2019-05-27<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.g2esports.com/welcome-uuno/|title=Welcome UUNO - Rainbow Six Siege Roster Update|date=2019-05-27|website=G2 Esports|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref>\n|[[Mousesports]]\n|[[Team Secret]]\n|-\n|{{flagicon|ESP}}\n|Daniel Mazorra Romero\n